<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>10th December 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on behalf of the British Poultry Council</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry industry is a key part of current and future food security for the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> because:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Poultry (mainly chicken) is consumed by 94% of the population, at a rate of 28.8 kg per person per year, and its po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pularity is increasing</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British poultry producers have integrated and short supply chains that are trustworthy and reliable</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British poultry producers are efficient users of resources, but face stiff challenges over the cost volatility of inputs, and in achi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eving long-term planning for development</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British poultry production has a flexible and resilient supply chain that has proven capable of dealing with unexpected circumstances, e.g. bird flu</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British poultry production is a model for sustainable intensificat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.69pt; padding-left:6.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British poultry production is unsubsidised</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British Poultry Council is the representative body of the British poultry meat industry. The Council addresses issues on all parts of the production chain: breeding, hatching, growing, and processing. BPC is the key link between member companies, gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nment, regulators and other stakeholders. BPC members represent almost 90% of the British poultry meat sector. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry meat sector is a dynamic, fast-paced modern food industry, producing consistently safe, affordable and environmentally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sustainable meat.</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Poultry accounts for around half (49%) of all meat eaten in the UK, almost the same volume as beef, pork and lamb combined, and consumption is set to increase further.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry meat industry produces around 875 million chickens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, 17 million turkeys, 16 million ducks, and 250,000 geese a year.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">35,4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">00 direc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t employees and an additional 37,9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">00 employees supported indirectly and through the wider supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2,500+ farms across the UK and 30 food production and other sites in the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">K.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BPC considers food security to be the most significant long-term issue facing the UK food sector. Its impact on the economy and productivity of this country, both as consumers and producers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, will be extremely damaging if not managed correctly.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK is a trading nation and must continue to be so while producing food according to its own strengths. The concepts of food security and self-sufficiency are often used as synonyms but the truth is that a high ratio in the latter does not guarantee the fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rmer. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry industry is a good example of how the two, separate, concepts must be balanced if UK food producers are to continue to grow their productivity to the economy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The economic contribution of the British poultry industry can be summa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rised as:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On its UK sales of £6.1 billion in 2012, the poultry meat industry made a £3.3 billion gross value added contribution to the UK GDP through its direct, supply chain, and wage consumption impacts</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For every £1 billion it contributes in gross value </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">added itself, the industry generates another £1.3 billion in the rest of the UK economy through its procurement and the wages paid to employees in its own businesses and across its supply chain</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The pou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ltry meat industry supports 73,3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">00 jobs in the UK, made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> up of 35,400 in the industry itself, 25,100 in its supply chain, and 12,800 in businesses that benefit from the spending of the wages by the industry and supply chain employers</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The industry supports £1 billion in total tax payable to the Exchequer, equiva</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lent to £36 for every household in the UK</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK is not self-sufficient in poultry meat. Of total consumption of around 2 million tonnes every year, 0.7 million tonnes was supplied by imports. We also export a significant amount of poultry meat, around 0.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3 million tonnes every year.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Poultry meat is now a global commodity, and while a large proportion of the UK trade is with other EU Member States there is a growing trade to and from third countries. The consumers’ demand for more affordable products has a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">llowed for a more open and flexible marketplace. UK produced poultry is dominant in the fresh meat market, while imported poultry is often found in the food service sector or value products. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have seen a shift in awareness among British consumers about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> provenance and the origin of their food, with more emphasis being placed on Br</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">itish and/or regional. Price still dominates choice, but the gap between it and other considerations has closed.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry industry is part of a global industry, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as such is subject to the volatility associated with livestock production. The British poultry meat sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, like other agri-food sectors, has been suffered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the volatility in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cost of grain. The costs of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">feed wheat, soyameal and corn, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which are the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">key feed ingredients for the poultry industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and a number of other sectors, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have been climbing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over the past few years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Feed already makes up half the cost of an oven-ready chicken so these increases have impacted on the cost of food and helped to push up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> inflation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The cost of UK feed has been rapidly rising and these sizeable cost increases will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">likely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lead to higher </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">food prices.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK poultry businesses, just like UK households, have been affected by the rising cost of utilities. The totality of these, fe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed costs, and labour costs all challenge the British poultry industry. Not all cost increases can be absorbed by the supply chain, and it still be expected to consistently provide the necessary quantities of affordable and wholesome food.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">try industry has grown on a purely commercial footing, receiving no subsidies or support. As a result it has an integrated and short supply chain whereby growing, slaughtering, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">packing are contained within a single company, and traceability and transpa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rency are inherent. Around 2,500 UK farms supply large slaughterhouses that are capable of processing birds at the rate of around 10,000+ per hour. This process is backed by rigorous assurance schemes that cover all aspects of production from bird health a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd welfare to ethical treatment of employees.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such short supply chains can contribute greatly to the overall resilience of food production in the UK. With sustainable intensification being the preferred option for future livestock production the poultry i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndustry is ideally placed to contribute, and grow that contribution, to UK food security.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry industry is facing challenges to deliver food to an ever increasing population. Costs of production and competition from imports have been mentio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ned but there are also some more domestic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and European,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> hurdles.</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Poultry production, both on-farm and slaughterhouse, is a highly technological process that needs continual investment to improve and grow the contribution to the UK, whether that’s new inno</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vations in poultry housing or more efficient equipment in the slaughterhouse.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Planning is a barrier for poultry production. The speed of decision making and the seemingly lower priority for agricultural buildings need to change dramatically</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recruitment is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a serious issue for long-term contribution, with fewer young people choosing agri-food, let alone the poultry industry. We have a dynamic and exciting industry but we need to change the perception, in the careers process, of what the industry can provide</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he cost of ever-tightening legislation is significant for food production</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no room for complacency if UK consumers are to enjoy stable supplies and reasonable food prices. It is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">important that food wastage is decreased, and it needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more widely acknowledged that the use of land and food crops to produce biofuels is having significant impact on food supply and prices.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The use of GM crops for feed will be an important element for future food security. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">BPC and its members believe that s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ociety’s acceptance of the ben</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">efits of GM food are essential.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">GM crops are highly regulated in terms of health and environmental safety. They have been used in the UK to feed other livestock destined for the retail supply chain and have been used to feed pigs, poultry, cattle and other livestock around the world for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the last 15 years, during which no ill effects have been reported or robustly reflected in peer reviewed research. Furthermore the independent European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) established in 2007 that recombinant DNA from GM plants used in feed does n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot end up in the final meat, milk or eggs. Importantly just like DNA and proteins that all animals ingest whenever they eat, it is rapidly broken down in the gut. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have seen the availability of Non-GM soya reducing as Brazilian growers produce more GM </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">varieties, many of which are more sustainable GM alternatives. Currently the poultry industry is paying a premium for non-GM soya even though the integrity of this product is deteriorating due to the use of common supply chains and lack of segregation. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is our view the future supply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on-GM soya will be limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Food security, even in its most basic sense of a guaranteed source of food sufficient for a nation’s population, will have a cost. At the very least due to an increase in population, but even m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ore so because of the societal pressures applied, such as: a desire for sustainable production, environmental considerations, animal health and welfare concerns, volatility of inputs, animal disease control, a preference for provenance. Any of these could,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and probably will, introduce a cost into the production system that will have to, eventually, be borne by the consumer.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As an example, the poultry industry globally is trying to find a way to eliminate campylobacter (a naturally occurring bacteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> can cause food poisoning illness). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This challenge has been embraced by the British poultry industry as necessary and beneficial, but there is a question of where the cost of doing so ultimately rests.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">New and emerging technologies can often mitigate some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cost increa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ses, but there is no guarantee and there is a limit of effectiveness. For poultry, and specifically broiler chickens, genetic selection for a range of qualities is reducing the amount of feed required per kilogram of meat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but this can be outpa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ced by volatility in feed prices.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The discussion on food security needs to start with an honest and realistic debate on the cost of food production and how that translates to the cost to the consumer. This coupled with reduction of food waste and educatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n about efficient use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of food will begin the process. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Efficient use of resources is good production practice in an unsubsidised industry, but that has to be matched at the consumption end.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The British poultry industry is ideally placed to support food </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">security at the present time, but it cannot achieve self-sufficiency across all areas where poultry is consumed. The increasing popularity of poultry (primary, ready to cook, ready meals, ready to eat, food service) is a welcome recognition of the qualitie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s inherent in British producers, but as a nation we will continue to need to trade.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For future food security the industry needs to overcome the challenges mentioned above, but with increasing consumption, low environmental footprint (indoor reared chicken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is second only to certain fish-farming methods in low global warming potential), and good standards of production, it has the potential to expand with demand.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK food cannot now be described purely in terms of UK production, but in poultry we have produc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers that can meet the challenge of food security, and to provide safe, affordable, and wholesome food for an increasing population. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would be happy to expand on any aspect of this submission.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>